animal.description:
Debbie is a 5-8 pound 2-month-old Goldendoodle/Coonhound mix with a lot of spunk and personality. This clever little girl wants to be anywhere people are and tends to stray from her siblings and marches to the beat of her own drum. Debbie is extremely loving with a desire to be held and cuddled by humans. She is the perfect pup for anyone who wants a partner in crime and a Netflix cuddle buddy. Debbie will probably grow to be 45-60 pounds and has been fostered with her littermates, a large dog, and a small dog. Her adoption fee is $400.00.


To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

Wiggles is a very sweet dog with people, very sweet. She has a lot of love for people but sadly because of the situation she was trapped in, she developed behavioral issues. She must remain inside Kentucky until the court case is resolved. If you have a suitable home and would like to try her as a foster, let us know!

NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet BRUTUS, see the contact information below.

Brutus is a beautiful, sweet 1-year-old Shepherd/Akita mix who was rescued off the streets of Tijuana. He is a lot of dog, but in a good way. Brutus is a neutered male and weighs about 75 lbs.

He is very inquisitive, eager to learn, and ready for fun. He is calm, playful, and loving, yet protective. He gets along well with other dogs and people. Brutus is housetrained and knows how to use a doggie door. He would be great with an individual or family who is active. He is ready to learn new things and he loves to ride in the car.

In addition to being neutered, Brutus has been wormed, microchipped, and is up-to-date with his Distemper/Parvo, Bordetella, and Rabies shots. He has been given Nexgard flea treatment.

An application for adoption will be requested, along with a video of your yard. There is a rehoming fee, and medical records will be provided. To meet Brutus, call, email or text PAM: 619.964.1181; email address is Pam.Lawless@gcccd.edu. This pet is being fostered in the East County of San Diego.

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Klaus is a big boy and about 4 months old and 25lbs. He is expected to be 70lbs as an adult. He is looking for a home of his own.
She is a strong willed guy who is working hard on his house training and loves to be social! Klaus absolutely loves affection and humans! He is currently in a foster home with an adult dog that he is 100% respectful of. She is helping him learn appropriateness and boundaries.. but his foster mom is also utilizing positive reinforcement training. This will also be a must for his forever home. We want to ensure that Klaus grows up to be the best breed ambassador and working with him on the puppy behaviors now is a key component to a healthy minded adult pitbull. 

We would love to see him in a home financially and emotionally ready for the first years of puppy hood and all that it brings! Training and education are very important part of this and if you cannot afford training currently then a strong willed pup like Klaus would not be the best fit for your home. He is quite the love bug and would love to meet and greet with you.

Adoption Process: PLEASE READ!
Klaus has a $300 adoption fee.
Anyone interested in meeting our adoptables must complete an online application, which is located on our website. This site is updated weekly so if an animal is listed they are available for adoption. Once the application is approved we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit and then before adoption is complete we will schedule a home check to ensure a safe environment for the animal you are looking to adopt. If you live outside of the Tri-County area we will do our best to accommodate a home visit but it will rely on the availability and volunteers at that time. At this time we cannot do out of the state adoptions. We also do not do on-the-spot adoptions and we do not adopt out animals by a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to fit everyone of our animals to the best match possible! We pride ourselves in responsibly placing animals in homes that are best fit for their needs.

www.redemptionrescuemi.com

animal.description: Biride is one of the dogs seized from the trixie foundation and she is in need of an experienced foster.  Birdie is not good with female dogs. She resource guards, hogs all the toys and is somewhat pushy. She is a very active dog. We noticed her pics at trixie tended to show her with her back to the fence or wall so she could watch everything and everyone. It was like she was always on high alert. Birdie did not engage in a lot of the fights. She had practically no scars but she was injured shortly before seizure as she had a pretty bad bite wound on her leg.  That does not make her sound too appealing, does it? The other side of Birdie is wonderful. She is loving with people, she likes to lay by your feet, she likes to have your attention, she takes treats out your fingers so nicely. She is also cat safe. She plays with cats quite well. And she is gorgeous.  Right now, Birdie is back in boarding. If you think you would like to foster her, please reach out! She must stay in Kentucky until the court case is resolved. We take care of her medical. She is spayed, UTD on vaccines, and on flea and tick and heartworm prevention. Birdie suffered at trixie. She is a highly intelligent dog that was trapped at the Gulag Of Despair. It is no wonder she has some issues. She just needs the right person and the right environment.

animal.description:
Phillip "Lip" is a 5-8 pound 2-month-old Goldendoodle/Coonhound mix who cannot resist the sounds of a squeaky toy and has the most perfect gray-brown eyes you will ever see. He is a social and content puppy, happy to chew on his sibling's ears or hang out on your lap while you read a book. Lip will probably grow to be around 55-70 pounds. He is eager to learn and please his humans and would do best with a forever home ready to give training and guidance to this young pup. Lip has been fostered with his littermates, a large dog, and a small dog.  His adoption fee is $400.00.


To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description:
Jovie is about 4 months old and looking for a home of her own.
She is a strong willed young girl who absolutely loves affection and humans! She is in a foster home with other dogs and is utilizing positive reinforcement training. This will also be a must for her forever home. We want to ensure that Jovie grows up to be the best breed ambassador and working with her on her puppy behaviors now is a key component to a healthy minded adult pitbull. 
We would love to see her in a home financially and emotionally ready for the first years of puppy hood and all that it brings! Training and education are very important part of this and if you cannot afford training currently then a strong willed pup like Jovie would not be the best fit for your home. She is quite the love bug and would love to meet and greet with you.
 
Adoption Process: PLEASE READ!
Jovie has a $300 adoption fee.
Anyone interested in meeting our adoptables must complete an online application, which is located on our website. This site is updated weekly so if an animal is listed they are available for adoption. Once the application is approved we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit and then before adoption is complete we will schedule a home check to ensure a safe environment for the animal you are looking to adopt. If you live outside of the Tri-County area we will do our best to accommodate a home visit but it will rely on the availability and volunteers at that time. At this time we cannot do out of the state adoptions. We also do not do on-the-spot adoptions and we do not adopt out animals by a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to fit everyone of our animals to the best match possible! We pride ourselves in responsibly placing animals in homes that are best fit for their needs.

www.redemptionrescuemi.com

animal.description: Hi! My name is Abigail, I'm a 3 year old couch potato. Okay, so I do like going on walks, but mostly I would like to be laid out on your comfiest spot cuddling my soft toys. I like to be wrapped in blankets and stay very still so you have no idea I am there. I am very loving and love to take naps with you. I can be hugged and will snuggle as close to you as I can whilst we sleep together. I love cuddly toys and am very gentle with them - I like to mother them and will carry them around so I can sleep with them. I know commands like sit', down and stay. I am cool with other dogs and used to live with more than 10+ in my old home, but I think ideally I would like to be the only princess in your house, please. People say I am very laid back and easygoing. Abigail is spayed, up to date on her vaccinations and microchipped. She is heartworm positive (not contagious to people or other animals) however the treatment for this is covered through our veterinarian. If you are interested in adopting Abigail or any of our other adoptable pets, please call our shelter at (985) 809-0183 to ask more questions or set up a private appointment. YES you can adopt if you live out of state, we do require you make the trip to us in person so Abigail and our staff can meet you. Her adoption fee for February is 10$, otherwise our adoption fee's are regularly $65.

animal.description:
Meet Ginger! She is a 2 year old, 28 pound, female, Labrador Mix. Ginger is a gentle soul who is looking for a nurturing home where she can continue to come out of her shell. Ginger’s signature place to spend her says is curled up on the couch or in the bed. She loves long relaxing naps and is slowly but surely getting the hang of walking outside on her leash. Ginger is not a natural city dog and will thrive in a suburban home with a backyard. She loves the company of other dogs and would love to have a furry sibling. We think Ginger could make a good family dog based on her calm and gentle demeanor. If you are looking for a loyal best friend and a warm cuddle buddy, look no further, Ginger is your girl! 

Ginger is spayed and up to date on her vaccinations. For more information about her, please fill out an application at www.ALRcares.com and email Leanna@alrcares.com. We schedule meet and greets for approved adopters only, an application is the first step in our approval process. Thank you!

animal.description:
We pulled this heavily pregnant mom out of a kill shelter in Alabama.  Just a few days later she gave birth to all these beautiful puppies.  They have been loved since the day they were born!  They are all ready for their new homes!  

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description: Meet Beau, short for Beauregard, a sweet, Southern gentleman who has found himself thousands of miles away from his preferred activities of attending Kentucky Derby parties and crawdad fishing. Beau is housetrained and his former family said he's a great, friendly, quiet dog. In play group, Beau was social with the other dogs, initiating and engaging in play with several other pups. Beau is just a young guy, but he'd love to get out of the shelter and into a home. If he sounds like the dog for you, put down that mint julip and make an appointment to meet him today.

animal.description: Wiggles (also known as Bennie) is part of the trixie foundation seizure. Wiggles is dog selective and is in boarding. She can do OK with one male dog approximately her size or larger but no females. Wiggles has a lot of battle scars from being stuck in the trixie foundation.  Wiggles is a very sweet dog with people, very sweet. She has a lot of love for people but sadly because of the situation she was trapped in, she developed behavioral issues. It was literally dog eat dog out there in that mud pit. It's a wonder more of the dogs did not have these issues.  We take care of all medical for her. She must remain inside Kentucky until the court case is resolved. If you have a suitable home and would like to try her as a foster, let us know!

animal.description:
Opie is a sweet male 10 month old, 40 pound Terrier, English Pointer & ??? mix. He is house-broken and crate-trained.

Opie does well with new people, he loves to play, and he is a cuddle bug when he isn't playing. He is a very active pup. So get those cuddles when you can!

Opie is a smart pup - he knows sit, stay, down and wait commands. He loves chewing on toys but had never chewed anything else.


Opie has lived in a household with a cat but the cat mostly ignored him. We are not sure how Opie does with other dogs so a Meet and Greet is highly recommended.


Opie would be best suited in a household without young (toddlers) children because of his energy level.

As long as Opie is on the website he is available. Applications can be found at CanineCollective.org

animal.description:
NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet BRUTUS, see the contact information below.

Brutus is a beautiful, sweet 1-year-old Shepherd/Akita mix who was rescued off the streets of Tijuana. He is a lot of dog, but in a good way. Brutus is a neutered male and weighs about 75 lbs.

He is very inquisitive, eager to learn, and ready for fun. He is calm, playful, and loving, yet protective. He gets along well with other dogs and people. Brutus is housetrained and knows how to use a doggie door. He would be great with an individual or family who is active. He is ready to learn new things and he loves to ride in the car.

In addition to being neutered, Brutus has been wormed, microchipped, and is up-to-date with his Distemper/Parvo, Bordetella, and Rabies shots. He has been given Nexgard flea treatment.

An application for adoption will be requested, along with a video of your yard. There is a rehoming fee, and medical records will be provided. To meet Brutus, call, email or text PAM: 619.964.1181; email address is Pam.Lawless@gcccd.edu. This pet is being fostered in the East County of San Diego.

animal.description:
Klaus is a big boy and about 4 months old and 25lbs. He is expected to be 70lbs as an adult. He is looking for a home of his own.
She is a strong willed guy who is working hard on his house training and loves to be social! Klaus absolutely loves affection and humans! He is currently in a foster home with an adult dog that he is 100% respectful of. She is helping him learn appropriateness and boundaries.. but his foster mom is also utilizing positive reinforcement training. This will also be a must for his forever home. We want to ensure that Klaus grows up to be the best breed ambassador and working with him on the puppy behaviors now is a key component to a healthy minded adult pitbull. 

We would love to see him in a home financially and emotionally ready for the first years of puppy hood and all that it brings! Training and education are very important part of this and if you cannot afford training currently then a strong willed pup like Klaus would not be the best fit for your home. He is quite the love bug and would love to meet and greet with you.

Adoption Process: PLEASE READ!
Klaus has a $300 adoption fee.
Anyone interested in meeting our adoptables must complete an online application, which is located on our website. This site is updated weekly so if an animal is listed they are available for adoption. Once the application is approved we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit and then before adoption is complete we will schedule a home check to ensure a safe environment for the animal you are looking to adopt. If you live outside of the Tri-County area we will do our best to accommodate a home visit but it will rely on the availability and volunteers at that time. At this time we cannot do out of the state adoptions. We also do not do on-the-spot adoptions and we do not adopt out animals by a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to fit everyone of our animals to the best match possible! We pride ourselves in responsibly placing animals in homes that are best fit for their needs.

www.redemptionrescuemi.com

animal.description: Biride is one of the dogs seized from the trixie foundation and she is in need of an experienced foster.  Birdie is not good with female dogs. She resource guards, hogs all the toys and is somewhat pushy. She is a very active dog. We noticed her pics at trixie tended to show her with her back to the fence or wall so she could watch everything and everyone. It was like she was always on high alert. Birdie did not engage in a lot of the fights. She had practically no scars but she was injured shortly before seizure as she had a pretty bad bite wound on her leg.  That does not make her sound too appealing, does it? The other side of Birdie is wonderful. She is loving with people, she likes to lay by your feet, she likes to have your attention, she takes treats out your fingers so nicely. She is also cat safe. She plays with cats quite well. And she is gorgeous.  Right now, Birdie is back in boarding. If you think you would like to foster her, please reach out! She must stay in Kentucky until the court case is resolved. We take care of her medical. She is spayed, UTD on vaccines, and on flea and tick and heartworm prevention. Birdie suffered at trixie. She is a highly intelligent dog that was trapped at the Gulag Of Despair. It is no wonder she has some issues. She just needs the right person and the right environment.

She is house trained, she know the basic commands of sit and lay down, and is not opposed to sleeping in her crate. She gets along well with other dogs and even children. animal.description:
We were pulling some dogs out of a kill shelter in Alabama and someone turned in this gorgeous puppy.  They said that they had found her.  We couldn't let her sit in a kill shelter!   

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Jovie is about 4 months old and looking for a home of her own.
She is a strong willed young girl who absolutely loves affection and humans! She is in a foster home with other dogs and is utilizing positive reinforcement training. This will also be a must for her forever home. We want to ensure that Jovie grows up to be the best breed ambassador and working with her on her puppy behaviors now is a key component to a healthy minded adult pitbull. 
We would love to see her in a home financially and emotionally ready for the first years of puppy hood and all that it brings! Training and education are very important part of this and if you cannot afford training currently then a strong willed pup like Jovie would not be the best fit for your home. She is quite the love bug and would love to meet and greet with you.
 
Adoption Process: PLEASE READ!
Jovie has a $300 adoption fee.
Anyone interested in meeting our adoptables must complete an online application, which is located on our website. This site is updated weekly so if an animal is listed they are available for adoption. Once the application is approved we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit and then before adoption is complete we will schedule a home check to ensure a safe environment for the animal you are looking to adopt. If you live outside of the Tri-County area we will do our best to accommodate a home visit but it will rely on the availability and volunteers at that time. At this time we cannot do out of the state adoptions. We also do not do on-the-spot adoptions and we do not adopt out animals by a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to fit everyone of our animals to the best match possible! We pride ourselves in responsibly placing animals in homes that are best fit for their needs.

www.redemptionrescuemi.com

animal.description:
Fiona is a 4-6 pound 2-month-old Goldendoodle/Coonhound mix who will melt your heart at first glance. She is the smallest one in her litter but does a good job of standing up for herself against her rowdier siblings. When meeting new people she can be very shy and timid, but once she's warmed up with a new person she is all cuddles. Fiona will probably grow to be around 45-60 pounds and would do wonderful in a home that allows a fair amount of play-time and socialization. She has been fostered with her littermates, a large dog, and a small dog. Her adoption fee is $400.00.


To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Abigail, I'm a 3 year old couch potato. Okay, so I do like going on walks, but mostly I would like to be laid out on your comfiest spot cuddling my soft toys. I like to be wrapped in blankets and stay very still so you have no idea I am there. I am very loving and love to take naps with you. I can be hugged and will snuggle as close to you as I can whilst we sleep together. I love cuddly toys and am very gentle with them - I like to mother them and will carry them around so I can sleep with them. I know commands like sit', down and stay. I am cool with other dogs and used to live with more than 10+ in my old home, but I think ideally I would like to be the only princess in your house, please. People say I am very laid back and easygoing. Abigail is spayed, up to date on her vaccinations and microchipped. She is heartworm positive (not contagious to people or other animals) however the treatment for this is covered through our veterinarian. If you are interested in adopting Abigail or any of our other adoptable pets, please call our shelter at (985) 809-0183 to ask more questions or set up a private appointment. YES you can adopt if you live out of state, we do require you make the trip to us in person so Abigail and our staff can meet you. Her adoption fee for February is 10$, otherwise our adoption fee's are regularly $65.

animal.description:
Meet Ginger! She is a 2 year old, 28 pound, female, Labrador Mix. Ginger is a gentle soul who is looking for a nurturing home where she can continue to come out of her shell. Ginger’s signature place to spend her says is curled up on the couch or in the bed. She loves long relaxing naps and is slowly but surely getting the hang of walking outside on her leash. Ginger is not a natural city dog and will thrive in a suburban home with a backyard. She loves the company of other dogs and would love to have a furry sibling. We think Ginger could make a good family dog based on her calm and gentle demeanor. If you are looking for a loyal best friend and a warm cuddle buddy, look no further, Ginger is your girl! 

Ginger is spayed and up to date on her vaccinations. For more information about her, please fill out an application at www.ALRcares.com and email Leanna@alrcares.com. We schedule meet and greets for approved adopters only, an application is the first step in our approval process. Thank you!

animal.description: Staff would describe my personality as: Shane is a very sweet samoyed who came to us as a stray, found in the city's dog park without an owner. He is very much a barker, so we are requiring ***NO APARTMENTS/CONDOS.*** Special preference may be given to adopters who have a history of samoyed ownership and/or a history of providing medical care to dogs. With other dogs I am: Good With cats I am: Good With children I am: Untested, but based on his personality would be guess he would do well Potty-trained: Yes Crate-trained: Unknown Leash-trained: Yes Tricks: Sit, Shake I have the following special needs: I need to gain weight! All dogs are tested for heartworms and given flea preventatives. They are also tested for intestinal parasites and receive routine dewormings. Dogs are vaccinated against distemper, rabies, and bordetella, spayed/neutered before adoption, and have a microchip. Adoption fees include the initial automated registration of the microchip at the time of adoption.

animal.description:
We pulled this heavily pregnant mom out of a kill shelter in Alabama.  Just a few days later she gave birth to all these beautiful puppies.  They have been loved since the day they were born!  They are all ready for their new homes!  

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption form on the website, or email messagemarybeth@gmail.com for any questions! 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/.

Meet June! June is an energetic sweetheart that is looking for her forever family. 

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Hi there!  My name's Goldie, what's your's?  I'm around 13 years old, and I was brought to the shelter and surrendered by my former family.  They had some health concerns and were no longer able to care for me, so now I'm here hoping that a nice new family will fall inlove with me and take me home.

The people here at the shelter have started me on some medicine to help my joints.  I'm an older girl, and my body doesn't work like it used to.  I still like to go for walks though!  I love getting to explore!

I'm hoping to find a quiet retirement home to spend my golden years in.  I would prefer a home without young kids, and I don't care for other dogs or cats so being an only pet is what I would like best.

More than anything I want to be loved.  Will you open your heart to a senior like me??  I promise I won't chew on your furniture like a little puppy would.  I would be content to nap the day away in a nice warm bed!

I'm up to date on vaccinations, spayed, and I also have a microchip.  All I need now is YOU!!

animal.description:
NEEDS to be ONLY dog, I’m DEAF, NO CATS, KIDS 5+

ADOPTION FEE $400 www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

Kratos, a beacon of strength, and that is exactly what I am. I am 3 years old, and I am deaf. I came to rescue after being put on the euthanasia list because I was deaf and no one wanted to take me home with them. Well, bad news for them is that I am AMAZING, good news for someone else, I AM AMAZING!!! Let me tell you a little about my story. Not much is known as to how I ended up in the shelter, but that really isn’t important because I am no longer there! I need to be the only dog in the house because I don’t like other dogs in my space. I do absolutely fine if I’m on a walk being around another dog, but being deaf, it’s hard to figure out what another dogs intentions are, so I just prefer not to have them in my home. I have a cat in my current foster home, and I love to chase him, but not because I want to be his friend. I am trying to catch him, so I can’t have any cats in my home. It’s preferred that I go to a home that has no small kids because of being deaf. Due to not being able to hear, I have to be ever vigilant of my surroundings because it’s the only way to know what’s going on, and little kids can tend to be very active and might not understand that I can’t hear them, so I get stressed out. NOW, let me tell you about all the amazing things about me. I am the worlds biggest cuddle bug and the most loving boy! I love to give the most passionate kisses, that just means a lot of licking lol, and will give you my paw to ask you to cuddle with me. I love to chew on toys, and I am a big chewer, so I will need some toys that can hold up to my chewing abilities. It’s calming for me to have something to chew on. I am fully potty trained and will sleep just fine in my kennel at night. My foster family is working on bell training to help me alert someone that I need to go outside, but I am doing well with a schedule also. My foster family is also working on some sign language that is basic to let me know what we are going to do. Right now I am learning what the sign is for bedtime so that I know to go to my kennel. I am working on my table manners and realizing that the food that is for people is not for me; personally isn’t that every dogs issue lol. I absolutely LOVE my foster human siblings, and I get so excited to see them. It’s going to be very important for me to have slow introductions with people because most of my input comes from my visual perspective, and it’s hard to read people  sometimes, so I just need a few extra moments. I love going for walks, but I pull on my leash because I get so excited, so we are working on how to calm my walking down. Again, everything is visual and smell to me, so I am just trying to figure everything out. I am going to need someone that is SUPER patient with me and wants to take their time with me to get me to learn and adjust to the world. I’ve not had any training before now, so I have just merely existed. This world is scary as it is, and I can’t hear, so it’s a little extra scary for me. If you think that you are up to the challenge, please fill out an application for me and let’s explore this new world together! Until I get to meet you, I will keep working on my sign language and learning all the new things I need to! Forever full of strength, Kratos (UPDATED 01/31/21)

animal.description:
Shila girl is ready to start the search for her forever family! <3

"Shila is our little spitfire. She has so much sass and personality! She will let you know if she doesn't like something through little growls and barks. She is outgoing and only likes to cuddle a little bit before seeing what trouble she can get into it. She is an explorer and has a slightly more active personality than some of her siblings. If you are looking for a girl with character, Shila is the girl for you! <3" 

Shila is a 6 week old female Great Pyrenees mix. She currently weighs about 10lbs. Our best guess is she will top out somewhere in the 70-80lb range. 

-Shila has been with us since birth. Her mom Varity came to us heavily pregnant. We are unsure of who her dad was. Varity's former owner believes it was a male Pyr mix who visits sometimes but doesn't know for sure. 

-Shila is still a baby. This means her new family needs to be ready to potty train her, work with her on basic manners, and have a lot of time on their hands to help raise her. 

-Shila will need proper socialization. Her new family will need to expose her to a little bit of everything. Such as walks, car rides, public outings, visitors, other dogs, etc. 

-Shila will not be ready to go home until February 22, give or take a couple of days. Anyone applying to adopt her needs to be able to bring her home close to that date. 

-Shila is being fostered in Kiowa, OK. We do not send our dogs on transports or ship them. This means his new family needs to pick him up, even if they are out of state. 

Think Shila is the girl for you?! If so, you can apply to adopt her at  https://www.pyrpawsandfluffytailsrescue.com/adoption-app

Her adoption fee is $275. That includes two sets of puppy shots, bordetella, and rabies. She will be micro-chipped, have a fecal done, be de-wormed, be spayed/neutered, and will be current on heart-worm and flea/tick prevention.

animal.description:
Frank a 5-8 pound 2-month-old Goldendoodle/Coonhound mix with a ton of energy and loves to be the center of attention. He will climb over all of his littermates and the playpen to get a little extra affection. Frank's favorite pastime is to roll around with his tennis balls all day to work on his pouncing technique. Frank has been fostered with his fellow littermates, a large, and small dog. He will probably grow to be around 55-70 pounds and would do best in a home with a yard and room to explore. His adoption fee is $400.00.


To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. animal.description:
I have an Adoption Pending and will be going home soon.  But I hope you will consider one of our other wonderful dogs in need.  Thank you!

Jeffery was found by a kind soul in Louisiana.  He is incredibly sweet and everyone who has met him has lost their heart to him!  He is likely a Golden mixed with some Collie and, of course, he is very cute!  He looks like a teddy bear with that fuzzy-wuzzy coat of his!

Jeffery is estimated to be about 8-10 months old.  He rides nicely in the car, is decent on a leash, and is good with other dogs.  He is an active fellow and will do well with an adopter who can give him the exercise a young dog needs.

Jeffery has been neutered and brought up to date on vaccinations.  He is heartworm negative and micro-chipped. 

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.  

If not yet approved for adoption, please visit our website to learn more and to submit an online application:     http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com/adoption-info1.html  

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  Please direct any questions regarding your application status to:  ajpillinger@gmail.com   

Thank you!
 
ABOUT OUR RESCUE
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, SGRR does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

SGRR ADOPTION FEES - Effective May 1, 2020  (subject to change)
  
  $750    Puppy - up to 6 months              
  $650    Young 6 months - 6 years            
  $550    Senior 7 - 9  years                       
  $450    Senior 10 years and older          
 
  $550    Young Special Needs                
  $400    Senior 7+ Special Needs                

$1000    Young Bonded Pair                   
  $900    Senior 7+ Bonded Pair         

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their SGRR dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their SGRR dog, SGRR must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this Sunshine dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a Sunshine dog.

Please visit our website at: http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com  to learn more about our rescue and to make a Donation to support Sunshine Golden Retriever Rescue.  

THANK YOU!

animal.description:
Maddy is enjoying long walks. Took her on a 2 mile hike on Saturday and she loved being out in the woods. She is a great sleeper and very quiet. Maddy loves attention and is very affectionate but not at all needy. She will sit for hours with her head in your lap if you let her. She follows commands really well and is totally housebroken. Great with other dogs and seems to do fine with cats -
when we walk and see a cat she doesn't seem too interested
. She will however chase a squirrel all day. She enjoys running around in a fenced yard. She is playful with toys and wants to tumble with her foster dogs.
Maddy would be a great addition for any type of family. She is wonderful with kids and also likes to chill out so an older pet owner would enjoy her and find her very easy as well. Those big brown eyes will suck you in for sure! Anyone would be lucky to have her.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hello Buffalo, meet Margo! She is a typical puppy - full of energy and fun, but then she crashes hard and naps quietly. She is incredibly fearless and curious, and enjoys wrestling with her canine siblings and playing tug with toys. Margo would do best in a home with a fenced yard and although she would be happy by herself, she would especially love an active canine sibling! Since Margo is young and would benefit from consistent training, she must go to a home without children under the age of 12.
Margo is super smart and very food motivated, so she picks up on training concepts quickly! With consistency, patience, and a routine, she is already learning basic manners in no time. She sleeps almost all night quietly in her crate and is starting to bark at the door when she has to go potty. If you think Margo would make the perfect addition to your family, both now and post-Covid, apply today at www.sadiesrescue.org .

Please keep in mind there are many factors to consider when choosing the right match for a puppy, so an application cannot guarantee adoption. Nor do we work on a 'first come first served' basis, but rather strive to find the best match for the personality of each dog. At the time of adoption, the puppy will be current on vaccinations and deworming. He or she will come with a pre-scheduled appointment at our vet to be spayed or neutered that the adopter is obligated to keep. The puppy will also be microchipped at this time. Our puppy adoption fee is $350 plus a $50 training deposit, which is refunded to the adopter when he or she provides proof of having completed a basic obedience class with their puppy. As part of our adoption process references, both personal and veterinarian, will be checked. Sadie's also requires a home visit before we adopt any of our dogs out; therefore we only adopt to our local WNY region. 2/2/21 7:45 AM

animal.description: Flokie  is a local owner surrender, He was originally adopted by  a young family 4 yrs ago from the Kootenai Humane Society. He had been transferred up from a high kill over crowded shelter in TX. He got along great with the familie's 3 young children, but as they've aged (both Floki & kids)  , and started having their frineds over, he's become over protective of them, and won't tolerate their friends playing rough, runnning or especially yelling/screaming around the house, and wrestling drives him nuts.   His owners have asked that i find a new home for him, without the bustling househokd containing young children. He prefers a more stable, calm regime, where he can take his naps in peace. He does need daily exercise, and as mush as you can dole out! Dalmations were bred to run alongside carriages pulled by horses, he can go for miles. A runner would be an ideal match for him. He does require a 6' fence. He also has extremely short hair, and not reallyy any on his underside, so cold weather is not his friend. This next bit is from his current owner;  "Hi I’m Floki! I am 5 years old and looking for a loving home.  I am a very protective of my family.  I need a large, spacious yard & alot of  exercise to be happy.  I’m probably the fastest runner you’ve seen, since a greyhound! I like to stretch out my legs and really cover ground.   I do not do well around young, rambuncious children, super important!!! Adults, and older children, that I know well, are great!  I have all of my shots and am very healthy.   I have never bitten anyone but there have been close calls when the kids get wild around me.  In all other ways, I am a wonderful dog. I love "couch time" snuggles and do have an "off" button in the house. Outside I like to romp, run, play fetch and show off my amazing athleticism. Im a very good boy in the house. I leave the trash alone and know how to stay on my pet bed. I come with all my vet records. animal.description:
MUST be the only dog, NO cats, KIDS 15+ only

ADOPTION FEE: $400 www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

 Hey there!! Let me introduce myself. My name is Cane, and I sort of have a very sad story, but I know that’s going to change now that I am in rescue. I am 6 years old, and my owner recently passed away. I was left alone and so scared. My owner had family, but they didn’t want to take me in. I was running around the streets for a bit before I found a porch that I thought looked safe, and so I went and sat on it and waited for someone to help me. It’s not known how I ended up running around, but I knew that wasn’t what I wanted. The porch that I found myself sitting on belonged to someone who had a friend that worked in rescue :) They offered to help me find somewhere to go so that I could find my forever home again, and now I am here and so happy. I’ve been here a couple of weeks, and everyone is getting to know me, so let me share with you what I have shared with them so far. I was not neutered, so I can be very dominant at times. I have an appointment scheduled to get that taken care of, so there is hope that I will settle some, but I am going to need a very dominant and strong handler either way. I respond well to men, but I think I would do just fine with a woman that was firm as well, but there can’t be any wiggle room in letting me have my way. I’ve been working really hard on following the rules, and I don’t want to go backwards on that. Don’t let having to be firm with me dissuade you from thinking that I don’t love to snuggle and be funny because I do! I absolutely love a good cuddle session on the couch or the floor. Now, it is assumed that I have never been kenneled before because I absolutely hate that thing. It’s a no go for me, but I do very well when I have just a small space that I can be in. They are still trying to get me to at least understand that the kennel is a safe and good thing, but I’m not having it. Due to being so dominant, I need to be the only dog, and there can’t be any cats in my new home. I am a stockier guy, and bossy, so younger kids are not an option for me. The kids in the home need to be 15 and older. They are still learning so much about me, and I am truly working hard, but I am going to be a work in progress for a bit, but I have faith that I will do awesome when I am completely settled and trusting people again. I know that my story seems like a lot and that I come with a lot of rules, but it’s truly to make me the best boy that I can be for the rest of my life. If you are up for the adventure, please fill out my application, and let’s see if we are a great match. Until we can meet, I am going to keep working on my manners and following all the rules and just being the best boy that I can be. Love you all, Cane (UPDATED 01/29/20)

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Coral is a lovely 1 year-old Blue Heeler/Lab mix female who was surrendered to a county dog shelter along with five other dogs including her sister Glory. The shelter told us that these dogs had lived outdoors and had limited interaction with people other than the person who fed them. When they arrived at the shelter, they were understandably terrified of everything but the shelter staff and volunteers were very patient with them as they had to get used to so many new things including walking on a leash. Both Coral and Glory made the trip to Canine Lifeline so they could relax in a foster home and get used to indoor life while searching for permanent new homes. We were pleasantly surprised to find when these two arrived here with us that they were not nearly as shy and skittish as we had expected. They still have a long way to go to become confident canines in new situations but Coral seems quite comfortable on a leash now and is getting the hang of crate-training and housetraining in her foster home. Coral is still shy with new people but absolutely loves meeting other dogs. She comes to life when she sees another dog and immediately wants to start playing. We do want to place Coral in a home where she'll have a canine buddy to help boost her confidence and show her the ropes. Given her shyness, she will also need a home with a secure aboveground fenced yard to allow her to play and explore her surroundings safely. Coral will need a person or family who is home much of the time as she will need to continue work on crate-training and housetraining as a puppy would. Lots of trips outdoors during the day are needed as she works on her house manners. If you've got the time and patience to help Coral live her best life, you're sure to be rewarded with a very loyal and devoted companion for years to come. There are no cats in Coral's foster home so we don't know how she would be living with them. Coral weighs about 40 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Coral. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Coral and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Charles!

The GHS family think's I'm awesome because I'm such a loving loyal dog! I'm a very smart boy who knows a lot of commands and tricks. I love attention, chin scratches, catching tennis balls and playing tug with rope toys. I am very food motivated, and I would do anything for a treat! When I'm getting pets I like to lay on my back and stretch my paws straight up into the sky and ask for belly rubs. I am a little older but I'm still very energetic! I love going on long walks where there are lots of things to sniff along the way. I also really love the snow, and get very excited, particularly when rolling around in it, digging in snowbanks or catching snowballs!

My new family should know that I can be anxious, so it usually takes me a little while for me to warm up a new place or to new people, but once I am comfortable, all I want is to be is by your side! If I'm feeling unsure I take a lot of comfort from my humans, as being beside them helps me feel more confident! I'm usually very well behaved, but sometimes I jump up when I get excited or when I want to play. I'm usually a pretty quiet dog in the house, although I will bark to let you know that someone is at the door or that I see people/dogs outside from the window. I have done well being alone for short periods at home, but I am not comfortable being in a crate, I'd rather be free to find a comfy spot in the house.

I'm really not a fan of other dogs or cats. I prefer to keep my distance outside and be the only animal in the house. Sometimes I bark or growl or try to run at them, so it's best if I'm given a lot of space when they are nearby. My foster mom has been working with me to make me more comfortable when I see other animals and I've made lots of progress! I haven't met any kids, but I would likely be best in a house without small children. It would be best for me to have my own outdoor space like a fenced in backyard, as it can be a stressful experience for me to be around other animals like off-leash dogs. I'm looking for a family that will use positive training methods to help me feel more confident when I am exploring the outdoors and new places with you! If you are looking for a lovable shadow, I'm the dog for you!

animal.description:
Hello everyone!  My name is Hugo and I have been waiting for my forever home at the shelter for awhile.  When I came in I was not a happy boy because the people I had been with before had been mean to me.  They had even held me down and used something that burned me to etch an "X" on my back!  Can you imagine how that felt?  As a result, I was afraid of hands coming toward me and tried to bite them.  But the people here have been kind to me and I have learned not to be afraid of hands and even enjoy being patted.  I sometimes forget myself and get nippy with sleeves and pant legs and they are teaching me not to do that too.  They have a trainer who would love to work with anyone interested in adopting me to teach them how to be with me.  But because I occasionally forget they say I should not go to a home with small children.

And I should mention that I LOVE going for car rides and walks in town. I behave really well when I do that because it makes me happy.  I so look forward to the day when someone will give me a chance and take me home and take me for lots of car rides and walks. And spend time with me so I don't have to be alone so much.  I like some dogs but not all so I should meet any other dog in the family before going home.  And did I mention that I like toys that squeak?

Thank you,
Hugo

Hey there world!! My name is Porter, and I came to rescue with my sister. I am 6 months old, and I am learning all things puppy that I need to learn. I am learning that my kennel is a good and safe place and that I can be quiet and okay in it and will go there when I hear “kennel up”. I am potty trained and am doing great in telling people that I have to go outside. I know sit and “place” when I come back in from outside. I am loving getting the chance to play with my foster fur brother. There are foster fur cats at my current home, and I sometimes will chase them, but it’s more out of curiosity. When they have had enough, they will correct me and I listen. I just want them to play with me, but they aren’t seeing things my way. I’m confident that we will be great friends though; well, that’s what I keep telling myself. I love playing with my toys and playing chase. I love snuggling with my foster mom and just being comfy on the couch. When I got to my foster home I wasn’t very confident, and I didn’t want to be away from people because everything scared me. I have been working really hard on this, and I am no longer scared and can do things by myself, and I realize that I don’t have to be right next to someone in order to feel safe. Well, if you are looking for an all around awesome little man, fill out my application, and let’s have a little meet and greet. Until I hear from you, I’m going to go back to trying to get the cat to understand that I love him and just want to play. Love, Porter (UPDATED 01/31/21)

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Yes, Jemma is stunning, but please read through her very honest bio before deciding she’s your dream dog. She was surrendered with some baggage that will take a special person and a fear-free vet to manage. Jemma is a velcro dog who attaches herself to a limited circle of trusted adults, which is great if you are following social distancing.  She has the typical “protective” Doberman personality, so previous breed experience is a plus for her success. She wants to have all of the attention to herself and is not a good candidate to live with other dogs or cats. She just turned 5 years old (DOB 11/5/15) and is a bigger gal at 85 lbs. Jemma knows some basic commands, but she would benefit from training to bond and communicate with her new person. Her give-up paperwork says she is housebroken, and she paws at the door to go out. In her foster home, she prefers not to be contained in a crate or x-pen, but she is trusted loose in certain areas with no issues. Jemma enjoyed a 6-foot privacy fence in her previous home and needs one in her new home, so only applicants with a fenced yard (no e-fence) will be considered. Her adopter will appreciate the fence because she pulls on leash. She will also require an obedience commitment, but she may appreciate one-on-one classes.

Why do the pretty ones always have baggage? Jemma shows some possessive behavior toward human beds, so our trainers recommend she not be allowed on your bed to avoid that behavior. Our vet has also prescribed her daily Prozac, which is helping her deal. During thunderstorms, fireworks, etc., Jemma would also benefit from an additional Rx anti-anxiety medication (Trazadone). At other times, she experiences anxiety attacks and needs to be calmed down, which is another reason why she needs to be the only dog and possibly have a single owner. Jemma can be stubborn and needs to be redirected at times. But she will show her foster dad affection and just loves spending time with him, curled up right next to him on the couch or chair.  Jemma will beg for food, but if ignored, she will walk away and go somewhere else.  She has a bad habit of counter surfing, so she will be good motivation to keep your counters clear. Jemma is a great watchdog, as she will bark at people and dogs walking by, so a single-family home is needed for her to be successful–a townhouse is too close to triggers. She is perfectly fine when left alone and will just curl up on the couch or chair. Like most Dobes, she likes to carry around a stuffed toy to cope with anxiety. If you are a single adult with a fenced yard and no kids, Jemma might be the girl for you!

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

What's your energy level like? I have a medium to high energy level!

What is it that staff and volunteers love about you? I am a super sweet girl who enjoys play time and walks!

Is there anything else we should know about you? I am 2 years old and I weigh between 65-70 pounds. I do have a medical waiver that states I have a broken canine tooth.

Meet the Rice Krispie Treats litter - Snap, Crackle & Pop! These three lab/pit mixes are 2 months old and weigh in between 8 to 10 pounds each. They love to play with each other, their toys and their foster parents! They are crate trained and working hard on potty training. Pop - Nicknamed “Big Pop” due to being the biggest of the three, Pop is a leader and splits his time between playing with his siblings and cuddling in his foster parents lap!

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description:
King is a 1.5 year old Great Pyrenees.  He and Princess were strays found wandering in rural MS.  King just wants love. He really enjoys human companionship likely because he never had it before.  He will definitely need some training as he likes to jump right up in your face to be loved on therefore he will not be placed in a home with young children. He also needs some leash work but he is going to make someone a fabulous companion.  King has been around other dogs however we will not place him in a home with another male dog.  He has seen cats at a distnce without issue but has not been around them directly. 

If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application on our website:                          https://.barkdogfarm.rescuegroups.org/forms/ 

Before applying be sure you have thoroughly researched Great Pyrenees.  They can be stubborn, prone to barking, overly protective and cannot be off leash.  You WILL NOT train a pyr to boundaries.  
Please be sure all family members are in agreement to adopting and your family is ready to bring dog home now. 
Applicants must be at least 21 years old. 
A volunteer will be in touch to discuss your application and the dog to determine if it is a good match. Your vet and two references will be called.  A virtual home visit done. Once approved a meet and greet at the farm will take place.  If all are in agreement and the animal has received its NH health certificate an adoption contract will be signed and adoption fee paid.  
Adoption fees for dogs are $450. for adults over 12 months, $500 for puppies 12 months and younger.  Fees for seniors, special needs or harder to place dogs will be determined by our Board of Directors.
 All dogs will be altered when adoption is finalized, up to date on age appropriate core vaccines, negative for parasites, heart worm and lyme tested if 6 months or older, microchipped and have a current health certificate.  
Proof of a basic obedience course completed is part of our adoption contract within six months. 
Our descriptions are based on shelter evaluations, input from foster homes and interactions with our volunteers therefore are in no way a guarantee of temperment. 

! Please know we practice Covid-19 guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing.  Only approved applicants are allowed to meet our dogs outdoors at this time. Please email barkingdogfrm@gmail.com with any questions.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Henry was brought into the Riverside shelter system by animal control officers with another dog. ACs believe the other dog had been attacking Henry, as he had bite marks and wounds on several spots. He also had a leather harness embedded in his chest. All of this tells us he was neglected and did not receive proper care. The shelter removed the harness and the wounds from it have healed, although he is still growing in fur where he was shaved so the harness could be removed. He is a sweet, loving boy who really enjoys walks and sniffing out the area. He is very motivated to chase small creatures so would not do well in a home with cats, rabbits, or small dogs. However, he gets along with and seems to enjoy the company of bigger dogs. He's a great size -- about 50 pounds -- and would make a loving companion. We aren't 100 percent certain he's house-trained but he is doing well, so we are sure he would be in a short time if he isn't already. He could use some basic training in areas such as sit, down, stay, etc. Henry is a bit scared of the car; we aren't sure what the reason is but his fosters are working on making the car a happy event that doesn't always end at the vet's office.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Glory is a beautiful 1 year-old Lab/Heeler mix spayed female with a very pretty medium-length coat. She was surrendered to a county dog shelter along with 5 other dogs. Apparently, the dogs had lived outside and had limited interaction with anyone other than the person feeding them. When they arrived at the shelter, they were understandably terrified of everything new and had absolutely no idea what to do on a leash. Glory and her sister Coral made the trip to Canine Lifeline so they could relax in a foster home and get used to indoor life while searching for permanent new homes. We were pleasantly surprised when these two arrived as they were not nearly as afraid of everything as we expected they would be. They had obviously gained much confidence during their stay at the shelter but are still going to be works in progress in their new homes. Glory seems happy to meet people although still shy and nervous in new situations. She is doing much better on a leash now and no longer flattens out when a leash is slipped over her head. She will walk but is still quite erratic and all over the place so can easily trip up her handler. Lots of daily practice in a quiet neighborhood will be perfect for her. Urban or high-density suburban life would be overwhelming for Glory so a home in a more rural area or quiet neighborhood is what she needs. Glory has been working on crate-training and housetraining in her foster home and is going to need to continue work on both in her adoptive home. She will need a person or family who is able to manage her like a puppy-getting her outside every hour or two during the day as she understands the house rules. Glory will also need a home with a yard that has a secure aboveground fence to help boost her confidence and keep her safe in a new environment. She does well with most other dogs although having had to fend for herself among a group of dogs has made her a little pushy with them. She will bully her sister over food so if there's another dog in her new home, mealtime will have to be closely managed. That said, Glory would benefit from having a calm, confident canine buddy in her new home to help show her the ropes. This beautiful pup is discovering toys and how much fun they can be-again, something that she likely never experienced before. This diamond-in-the-rough is going to become an outstanding companion for the person or family who has the time and patience to work with a young dog who needs to make up for lost time. Glory weighs about 40 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Glory. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there.

Hello, my name is Cash and I am here with my sister. I am the pretty, tan one!  I am about 12 weeks young and I am a Shepherd/ Cattle mix. I weight 25 lbs and my foster mom tells me that I am going to be a Runway model.  Tall and beautiful!  
We were dropped off at the shelter when we were little babies and my sister Pluto and I have been together all this time. It would be nice if we could stay together since we are thick as thieves. That is how our foster mom describes us.  You know any sisters getting along?  We sure do!
I love to play, play play and rough house with Pluto. We are really smart and have already learned our manners and we know to go outside to do your business. Our foster mom just claps her hands and we know to come back inside. 
We just love the snow. As a matter of fact we have been playing in the snow the entire morning. We chase each other and roll and frolic in the snow. Foster mom tells that we better not make a mess when we get back inside. 
I am ready to go to our forever family. I hope my sister and I can go together but that is just my wish. I can't wait to learn everything I need to know to because a Lady. I promise I will put a smile on your face every day of my life and will warm your heart at night. Until we meet, 
Love, 
Cash, other wise known as the Runway model.

To meet Cash please complete an adoption application at www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org
Cash is fostered in New Lenox, IL. Sorry we cannot adopt out of the state of IL. Due to the large number of applications we might not be able to get back to you so please check our website for updates on Cash's adoption status. www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21
